    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "\"Experience\" as main, \"empirical experience\" for disambiguation only",
    "content": "**\"Experience\" as main translation, with \"empirical experience\" as the disambiguating form.**\n\nReasoning: 经验 in Chinese is the normal, unmarked word for \"experience\" -- it is not a technical or marked term. Adding \"empirical\" every time would over-translate. In the section headers (经验的总结, 经验的预测, 经验的抽象), plain \"experience\" reads naturally: \"the summary of experience,\" \"the prediction of experience,\" \"the abstraction of experience.\" The reader understands from context that this is accumulated, empirical experience.\n\nReserve \"empirical experience\" for the rare cases where 经验 and 体验 appear in close proximity and disambiguation is needed, or where the author uses 经验性的 (which genuinely means \"empirical\" as an adjective).\n\nIn practice, 经验 and 体验 almost never appear in the same sentence in this corpus. The collision risk is theoretical, not practical. When it does occur, the disambiguating form is available. But the main dictionary entry should be the natural English word: \"experience.\""
  }
}
